# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: wireless-power-transfer
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:wireless-power-transfer/inductive-charging] Inductive charging transfers energy through inductive coupling: alternating current passes through an induction coil, generating a fluctuating magnetic field, which creates an induced alternating electric current in a nearby secondary coil.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/inductive-charging] The alternating current can be rectified to a direct current which charges a battery or provides operating power.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/inductive-charging] Greater distances between sender and receiver coils, such as those required for wirelessly charging electric vehicles, can be achieved with resonant inductive coupling.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/inductive-charging] The alternating current of the system can use a resonance frequency tuned with capacitors to create a transmitter and receiver LC circuit with a specific resonance frequency.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/inductive-charging] The frequency is chosen depending on the distance desired for optimal efficiency, and as of 2025 the frequency is commonly 85 kHz.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/inductive-charging] Some systems use inductive loops made of Litz wire surrounding ferrite cores.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/inductive-charging] Charging efficiency is sensitive to lateral, longitudinal, and vertical misalignment.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/inductive-charging] Misalignment of more than 3 cm (1.2 in) can severely lower power transfer.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/inductive-charging] Some systems align their coils by having the receiver coils mounted on a movable arm that can be lowered closer to the transmitter coils, for example it can be lowered from the underside of a truck closer to a transmitter coil on the ground.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/inductive-charging] Applications of inductive charging can be divided broadly into low power and high power.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/inductive-charging] Low power applications generally target consumer electronic devices such as cell phones, handheld devices, computers, and similar devices which normally require power below 100 watts.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/inductive-charging] The AC utility frequency of 50 or 60 hertz is often used, or in the case of Qi-compliant devices, frequencies in the range of 87 to 205 kHz are typical.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/inductive-charging] Some methods, such as resonant inductive coupling, can maintain charging at a distance of a few inches between the transmitter and receiver coil, though foreign objects pose a fire or burn risk if metals or organisms are between the active coils for high-power systems.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/inductive-charging] High power inductive charging generally refers to power above 1 kilowatt.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/inductive-charging] Such power is required for electric vehicles, and some implementations reach 300 kilowatts or higher.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/inductive-charging] High-power inductive charging systems use resonant inductive coupling for higher efficiency.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/inductive-charging] These systems are usually implemented in the long wave range of frequencies in the tens of kilohertz, commonly 85 kHz as the regulatory allowable noise levels are higher at this range than surrounding ranges.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/inductive-charging] Short wave frequencies can enhance the system's efficiency and size but they're not used because they would create radio interference worldwide.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/inductive-charging] High power at 85 kHz raise the concern of electromagnetic compatibility and radio frequency interference over background noise levels at ranges of up to 300 km (190 mi).
[src:wireless-power-transfer/inductive-charging] Inductive charging offers protected connections free of need of corrosion protection.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/inductive-charging] Induction circuits offer protection from faults such as short circuits due to insulation failure, especially where connections are made or broken frequently.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/inductive-charging] Without the need to constantly plug and unplug the device, there is significantly less wear and tear on the socket of the device and the attaching cable.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/inductive-charging] For embedded medical devices, the transmission of power via a magnetic field passing through the skin avoids the infection risks associated with wires penetrating the skin.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/inductive-charging] Automatic operation of inductive charging in roads can allows vehicles to operate without charging stops through opportunity charging over inductive coils embedded in the road.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/inductive-charging] Due to the lower efficiency of inductive charging compared to conductive charging, devices took 15 percent longer to charge when supplied power is the same amount when tested in 2018.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/inductive-charging] An amateur 2020 analysis of energy use conducted with a Pixel 4 found that a wired charge from 0 to 100 percent consumed 14.26 Wh (watt-hours), while a wireless charging stand used 19.8 Wh, an increase of 39%.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/inductive-charging] Using a generic wireless charging pad and mis-aligning the phone produced consumption up to 25.62 Wh, or an 80% increase.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/inductive-charging] The analysis noted that while this is not likely to be noticeable to individuals, it has negative implications for greater adoption of smartphone wireless charging.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/inductive-charging] Inductive chargers produce more waste heat than wired chargers, which may negatively impact battery longevity.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/inductive-charging] Waste heat is a concern for high-power implementations of inductive charging for transportation.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/inductive-charging] Trials in France in 2023 found risk of thermal damage to the road under regular operating conditions due to the induction coils exceeding temperatures of 100 °C (212 °F).
[src:wireless-power-transfer/inductive-charging] The most commercially-successful standard for compatibility between inductive chargers and small electronic devices is the Qi standard, which started development in 2008 and was first published in 2010.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/inductive-charging] Qi quickly expanded in the mid 2010s, and after a period of having three competing standards Qi became ubiquitous by the mid 2020s.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/inductive-charging] Other standards include: Power Matters Alliance (PMA), which was publicly announced in January 2012; and Rezence, which was developed by the Alliance for Wireless Power (A4WP) and merged with PMA in 2015 under the AirFuel name.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/inductive-charging] A group was launched in May 2010 by the Consumer Electronics Association to set a baseline for interoperability for chargers.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/inductive-charging] General Motors, Toyota, and Ford expressed interest in the technology and the standards effort.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/inductive-charging] Daimler's Head of Future Mobility, Professor Herbert Kohler, expressed caution and said in 2011 that the inductive charging for EVs was at least 15 years away, and the safety aspects of inductive charging for EVs have yet to be looked into in greater detail.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/inductive-charging] Magne Charge, also known as J1773, is an electric vehicle inductive charging system formerly available from General Motors.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/inductive-charging] The first standard for vehicle wireless charging was the SAE J2954 standard, published in 2020.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/inductive-charging] It allows inductive car charging over a pad, with power delivery up to 11 kW.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/inductive-charging] The standard provides a methodology for activating the charger only when sufficient alignment is detected.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/inductive-charging] Development began in the early 2020s for standards for higher-power wireless charging and charging while driving.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/inductive-charging] Coordination was initiated in 2026 for the development of a standard for vehicle-to-grid wireless charging by SAE Group Europe, Denso Germany, Toyota Motor Europe, ABB, Fraunhofer, University of Leeds, and others.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/inductive-charging] Development of technologies and standards for charging-while-driving, or dynamic wireless power transfer (DWPT), continued in the 2020s by several organizations.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/inductive-charging] Among them: Utah State University, Purdue University, the University of Auckland, Vedecom, ENRX (formerly IPT), and Magment.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/inductive-charging] SAE International has started developing standards for dynamic wireless power transfer in 2023.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/inductive-charging] An Electreon representative stated in a podcast published in December 2023 that SAE, Electreon, and other organizations are jointly developing a standard for dynamic wireless inductive charging.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/inductive-charging] Electreon has also collaborated in the early 2020s on standardization with the Michigan Department of Transportation and WiPowerOne, an offshoot of the KAIST OLEV project.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/inductive-charging] IPT (which later became a subsidiary of ENRX) has been working on its PRIMOVE system that uses inductive cables instead of coils; they regard existing standards which use coils as "extremely expensive" for dynamic charging.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/inductive-charging] Manufacturers of smartphones have started adding inductive charging technology into their devices in the late 2010s, the majority adopting the Qi wireless charging standard.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/inductive-charging] Some battery-powered devices offer wireless bidirectional charging, allowing a charged device to charge the battery of another device.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/inductive-charging] Similarly, research in Germany by BASt in 2025 estimated 76%–81% overall efficiency for heavy goods transport.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/inductive-charging] Trials in Norway in 2025 found that coil misalignment of more than 3 cm (1.2 in) can severely lower power transfer.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/inductive-charging] SAE International notes that wireless charging systems do not have well-established foreign object detection technologies, and proposes establishing safety tests for these technologies.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/inductive-charging] Foreign objects pose a fire or burn risk if metals or organisms are between the ground pad and the receiver when the system is active.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/inductive-charging] Le-Blanc proposed in 1894 an apparatus and method to power an electric vehicle with inductive power transfer.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/inductive-charging] At the time, combustion engines proved more popular, and this technology was not widely implemented.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/inductive-charging] In 1972, Professor Don Otto of the University of Auckland proposed a vehicle powered by induction using transmitters in the road and a receiver on the vehicle.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/inductive-charging] Bolger, Kirsten, and Ng implemented in 1978 an electric vehicle powered by inductive power transfer at a frequency of 180 Hz and power of 20 kW.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/inductive-charging] An inductive-charging bus was operated in the 1980s in California, and similar developments in inductive power transfer were being explored in France, Germany, and other European countries.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/inductive-charging] Wireless charging of an electric vehicle while driving is known as "dynamic wireless charging" or "dynamic wireless power transfer", DWPT.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/inductive-charging] The first working full-scale DWPT prototype is generally regarded to have been developed at the University of California, Berkeley in the 1980s and 1990s.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/inductive-charging] The first commercialized DWPT system, Online Electric Vehicle (OLEV), was developed as early as 2009 by researchers at the KAIST.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/inductive-charging] Vehicles using the system draw power from a power source underneath the road surface, which is an array of inductive rails or coils.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/inductive-charging] There have been efforts to standardize dynamic wireless power transfer in the 2020s.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/inductive-charging] The main technical challenge of DWPT is low efficiency.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/inductive-charging] The German Ministry of Economy, BMWK tested in-road wireless EV charging infrastructure implemented by Electreon in 2023.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/inductive-charging] The tests included a bus equipped with inductive coils that receive power from a 200-meter strip of transmitters under the road surface.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/inductive-charging] The receivers were able to collect 64.3% of the energy emitted from the transmitters.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/inductive-charging] Installation proved complex and costly, and finding suitable locations for the coils' roadside power cabinets proved difficult.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/inductive-charging] Commercialization efforts of the technology have not been successful because of high costs in the 2010s and 2020s.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/inductive-charging] The cost of a single wireless electric lane at 50% coverage at large-scale deployment was estimated in 2021 to be about 6.5 million dollars per mile.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/inductive-charging] A study about wireless inductive electric road systems found, using data from BRTdata.org for the year 2025, that a wireless charging lane would not be cost-effective for most bus rapid transit (BRT) systems around the world, with the exception of the ones in Beijing, Xiamen, and Bogotá.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/inductive-charging] Cost-effectiveness requires a combination of high fleet utilization and high traffic density: utilization is given by the ratio of traveling buses to the total available bus fleet, and density is given by the number of traveling buses per mile of bus lane.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/inductive-charging] The study assumes a wireless power transfer efficiency of 90%, installation of the minimal length of wireless charging infrastructure required to meet fleet charging needs, and a fixed cost of $3M per wireless charging infrastructure mile and an additional cost of $10k per kW-mile.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/inductive-charging] This gives, for example, a cost of $4M per mile for a 100 kW wireless charging system, where the 100 kW system is more expensive per mile than a 50 kW or 25 kW system, but requires less miles of charging lanes.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/inductive-charging] Inductive charging infrastructure was found in 2017 to increase the occurrence of reflective cracks in road surfaces.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/inductive-charging] Testing of various bonding materials between the inductive coils and the asphalt in 2023 at Nantes showed that standard installation techniques of inductive coils under the asphalt were not satisfactory and resulted in critical strains.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/inductive-charging] Performance was satisfactory with the use of specific bonding resins, with non-critical degradation in performance compared to reference pavements with no inductive coils.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/inductive-charging] Despite satisfactory results, even the best-performing methods showed risk of debonding of the casing of the coils from the top layer of the road. ÉTS and Université Laval studied the structural performance of in-pavement inductive coils in 2025, similarly finding evidence of debonding.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/inductive-charging] The 2023 Nantes trials showed increased risk of thermal damage to the road under regular operating conditions due to the induction coils exceeding temperatures of 100 °C (212 °F).
[src:wireless-power-transfer/inductive-charging] INDOT has been testing in 2024 a DWPT installation with special polymer-concrete previously used for bridges.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/inductive-charging] Wireless charging is making an impact in the medical sector by means of being able to charge implants and sensors long-term that is located beneath the skin.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/inductive-charging] Multiple companies offer rechargeable medical implant (e.g. implantable neurostimulators) which use inductive charging.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/inductive-charging] Researchers have been able to print wireless power transmitting antenna on flexible materials that could be placed under the skin of patients.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/inductive-charging] This could mean that under skin devices that could monitor the patient status could have a longer-term life and provide long observation or monitoring periods that could lead to better diagnosis from doctors.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/inductive-charging] These devices may also make charging devices like pacemakers easier on the patient rather than having an exposed portion of the device pushing through the skin to allow corded charging.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/inductive-charging] This technology would allow a completely implanted device making it safer for the patient.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/inductive-charging] It is unclear if this technology will be approved for use – more research is needed on the safety of these devices.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/inductive-charging] While these flexible polymers are safer than ridged sets of diodes they can be more susceptible to tearing during either placement or removal due to the fragile nature of the antenna that is printed on the plastic material.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/inductive-charging] While these medical based applications seem very specific the high-speed power transfer that is achieved with these flexible antennas is being looked at for larger broader applications.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/qi-standard] Qi version 1.0 was released in 2010; by 2017, it had been incorporated into more than 200 models of smartphones, tablets, and other devices.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/qi-standard] In December 2023, 351 manufacturers were working with the standard, including Apple, Asus, Google, Huawei, LG Electronics, Samsung, Xiaomi, and Sony.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/qi-standard] The Qi specification version 2.2, released in April 2025, supports charging speeds of up to 25 watts and aims to improve compatibility across devices from various manufacturers.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/qi-standard] The current version 2.2.1 released in July 2025 includes Qi2 25W branding for the 25 watt charging mode.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/qi-standard] The name of the Qi standard comes from the Chinese word *qì* (simplified Chinese: 气; traditional Chinese: 氣), meaning "life force" or "vital energy".
[src:wireless-power-transfer/qi-standard] Devices that operate using the Qi standard rely on electromagnetic induction between planar coils.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/qi-standard] A Qi system consists of two types of devices – the Base Station, which is connected to a power source and provides inductive power, and Mobile Devices, which consume inductive power.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/qi-standard] The Base Station contains a power transmitter that comprises a transmitting coil that generates an oscillating magnetic field; the Mobile Device contains a power receiver holding a receiving coil.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/qi-standard] The magnetic field induces an alternating current in the receiving coil by Faraday's law of induction.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/qi-standard] Close spacing of the two coils ensures the inductive power transfer is efficient.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/qi-standard] Base Stations typically have a flat surface – referred to as the Interface Surface – on top of which a user can place one or more Mobile Devices.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/qi-standard] There are two methods for aligning the transmitting coil (part of the Base Station) and receiving coil (part of the Mobile Device) in order for a power transfer to happen.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/qi-standard] In the first concept – called guided positioning – a user must place the Mobile Device on a certain location of the Base Station's surface.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/qi-standard] For this purpose, the Mobile Device provides an alignment aid that is appropriate to its size, shape, and function.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/qi-standard] The second concept – referred to as free positioning – does not require the user to place the Mobile Device in direct alignment with the transmitting coil.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/qi-standard] There are several ways to achieve free positioning.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/qi-standard] In one example a bundle of transmitting coils is used to generate a magnetic field at the location of the receiving coil only.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/qi-standard] Another example uses mechanical means to move a single transmitting coil underneath the receiving coil.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/qi-standard] A third option is to use a technique called *Multiple Cooperative Flux Generators*.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/qi-standard] The power transmitter includes a power conversion unit and a communications and control unit.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/qi-standard] Figure 1-1 shows the transmitting coil (array) generating the magnetic field as part of the power conversion unit.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/qi-standard] The control and communications unit regulates the transferred power to the level that the power receiver requests.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/qi-standard] A Base Station may contain numerous transmitters, allowing for multiple Mobile Devices to be placed on the same Base Station to charge each of its batteries.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/qi-standard] A power receiver comprises a power pick-up unit, and a communications and control unit.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/qi-standard] A power pick-up unit typically contains a single receiving coil only.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/qi-standard] The mobile device it charges typically contains a single power receiver.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/qi-standard] The communications and control unit regulates the transferred power to the level that is appropriate for the device.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/qi-standard] A reference Qi low-power transmitter has a coil of 20 turns (in two layers) in a flat coil, wound on a form with a 19 mm inner diameter and a 40 mm outer diameter, with a below-coil shield of soft iron at least 4 mm larger in diameter which gives an inductance of 24 ± 1 microhenries.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/qi-standard] This coil is placed in a series resonant circuit which is driven by an H-bridge switching arrangement from the DC source.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/qi-standard] Power control is automatic and voltage is controllable in steps of 50 millivolts or less.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/qi-standard] In the device a proportional-integral-derivative controller is used to modulate the delivered power according to the primary cell voltage.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/qi-standard] Other Qi charge transmitters start their connections at 140 kHz, but can adjust to find a frequency to better match the distance between coils.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/qi-standard] Different Qi reference designs have different coil arrangements, including oval coil and multi-coil systems as well as more complex resonance networks with multiple inductors and capacitors.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/qi-standard] These designs allow operation at frequencies from 105 to 205 kHz and with maximum resonant circuit voltages as high as 200 volts.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/qi-standard] The Qi power receiver hardware reference design starts with a rectangular coil of wire 44 mm × 30 mm outside size, with 14 turns of wire, and with an above-coil magnetic shield.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/qi-standard] Power output to the portable device is via a full-wave bridge; the power is typically filtered with a capacitor before delivery to the charge controller.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/qi-standard] Other Qi power receivers use alternate resonance modulators, including switching a resistor or pair of resistors across the receiver resonator capacitor, both before and after the bridge rectifier.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/qi-standard] The Wireless Power Consortium (WPC) published the Qi low-power specification in August 2009.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/qi-standard] The Qi specification can be downloaded freely after registration.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/qi-standard] Under the Qi specification, "low power" inductive transfers deliver power below 5 W using inductive coupling between two planar coils.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/qi-standard] These coils are typically 5 mm apart but can be up to 40 mm and possibly further apart.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/qi-standard] The Qi low-power specification has been renamed to the Qi Baseline Power Profile.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/qi-standard] Regulation of the output voltage is provided by a digital control loop where the power receiver communicates with the power transmitter and requests more or less power.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/qi-standard] Communication is unidirectional from the power receiver to the power transmitter via backscatter modulation.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/qi-standard] In backscatter modulation, the power-receiver coil is loaded, changing the current draw at the power transmitter.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/qi-standard] These current changes are monitored and demodulated into the information required for the two devices to work together.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/qi-standard] In 2011, the WPC began to extend the Qi specification to medium power.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/qi-standard] As of 2019, the Medium Power standard currently delivers 30 to 65 W.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/qi-standard] It is expected to eventually support up to 200 W (typically used for portable power tools, robotic vacuum cleaners, drones and e-bikes).
[src:wireless-power-transfer/qi-standard] In 2015, the WPC also demonstrated a high-power specification, called "Ki", that will deliver up to 1 kW, allowing the powering of kitchen appliances among other high-power utilities.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/qi-standard] In 2015, WPC introduced the Qi Extended Power Profile specification which supports charging phones at up to 15 W.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/qi-standard] Phone companies that support this include LG, Sony, Xiaomi, and Sharp.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/qi-standard] In 2024, WPC upgraded Ki to support 2.2 kW wireless power delivery.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/qi-standard] WPC introduced Proprietary Power Delivery Extension to allow phone OEMs to deliver higher than Baseline Power Profile's 5 W or the Extended Power Profile's 15 W.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/qi-standard] Currently, only Samsung has published their compliance test.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/qi-standard] Other phone companies that use proprietary standards for fast wireless charging include Apple, Huawei and Google.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/qi-standard] With Qi version 2.0, WPC introduced Magnetic Power Profile (MPP), an optional part of the specification based on Apple's MagSafe for iPhone.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/qi-standard] This enables magnetic attachment and alignment with a ring of permanent magnets around the charging coil and is backwards compatible with MagSafe devices.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/qi-standard] Devices which implement MPP use a new logo and branding, Qi2 in a circle, to distinguish them from Qi devices that do not support MPP (even if they otherwise support Qi v2.0 or later).
[src:wireless-power-transfer/qi-standard] The "Qi2 in a circle" logo has previously been sporadically used for Qi2 without MPP, this usage is officially disapproved for new products.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/qi-standard] Previously Qi(1) products are to be labeled as Qi2, as use of the Qi(1) logo has been discontinued.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/qi-standard] Nokia first adopted Qi in its Lumia 920, and Samsung Mobile on the Galaxy S3 (supported via a retrofittable official Samsung back cover accessory) in 2012, the Google/LG Nexus 4 followed later that year.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/qi-standard] Toyota began offering a Qi charging cradle as a factory option on its 2013 Avalon Limited, with Ssangyong the second car manufacturer to offer a Qi option, also in 2013.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/qi-standard] As the Qi standard gained popularity, *Qi Hotspots* began to arise in places such as coffee shops, airports, sports arenas, etc.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/qi-standard] In 2012, The Coffee Bean and Tea Leaf, a US coffee chain, announced plans to install inductive charging stations at selected major metropolitan cities, as did Virgin Atlantic, for United Kingdom's London Heathrow Airport, and New York City's John F.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/qi-standard] In 2015, a survey found that 76% of people surveyed in the United States and China were aware of wireless charging (an increase from 36% the previous year), and 16% of those were using it daily.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/qi-standard] Furniture retailer IKEA introduced lamps and tables with integrated wireless chargers for sale in 2015, and the Lexus NX gained an optional Qi charging pad in the center console.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/qi-standard] An estimated 120 million wirelessly charging phones were sold that year, notably the Samsung Galaxy S6, which supported both Qi and the competing Power Matters Alliance standards.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/qi-standard] By early 2017, Qi had displaced other competing standards such as Rezence.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/qi-standard] On September 12, 2017, Apple announced that their new smartphones, the iPhone 8, iPhone 8 Plus, and the iPhone X, would support the Qi standard.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/qi-standard] Since then, every new iPhone version has supported the Qi wireless charging standard.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/qi-standard] Apple also announced plans to expand the standard with a new protocol called AirPower, which would have added the ability to charge multiple devices at once; however, this was canceled on March 29, 2019.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/qi-standard] By the initial launch of iOS 17 in 2023, Apple launched the iPhone 15 models and iPhone 15 Pro models to support the fast 15 W Qi2-certified wireless charging.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/qi-standard] With iOS 17.2, Apple added the fast 15W Qi2-certified wireless charging support for the iPhone 13 models, iPhone 13 Pro models, iPhone 14 models and iPhone 14 Pro models.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/qi-standard] In July 2024, HMD Global announced the Skyline, which became the first Android device to support the Qi2 MPP standard.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/qi-standard] In January 2025, Samsung announced that their latest Galaxy S25 series phones are "Qi2 Ready".
[src:wireless-power-transfer/qi-standard] This means that while the devices themselves do not have magnets built-in, they are fully compatible with Qi2 when paired with a magnetic case.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/qi-standard] In August 2025, the Google Pixel 10 range became the first major Android phones to include built-in magnets for Qi2 MPP.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/qi-standard] The Google Pixel 10 Pro XL also became the first device to support the new Qi2 25W standard.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/resonant-inductive-coupling] Various resonant coupling systems in use or are under development for short range (up to 2 meters) wireless electricity systems to power laptops, tablets, smartphones, robot vacuums, implanted medical devices, and vehicles like electric cars, SCMaglev trains and automated guided vehicles.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/resonant-inductive-coupling] The Tesla coil is a resonant transformer circuit used to generate very high voltages, and is able to provide much higher current than high voltage electrostatic machines such as the Van de Graaff generator.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/resonant-inductive-coupling] Resonant transformers are widely used in radio circuits as bandpass filters, and in switching power supplies.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/resonant-inductive-coupling] In 1894 Nikola Tesla used resonant inductive coupling, also known as "electro-dynamic induction" to wirelessly light up phosphorescent and incandescent lamps at the 35 South Fifth Avenue laboratory, and later at the 46 E.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/resonant-inductive-coupling] Houston Street laboratory in New York City.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/resonant-inductive-coupling] In 1897 he patented a device called the high-voltage, resonant transformer or "Tesla coil." Transferring electrical energy from the primary coil to the secondary coil by resonant induction, a Tesla coil is capable of producing very high voltages at high frequency.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/resonant-inductive-coupling] In the early 1960s resonant inductive wireless energy transfer was used successfully in implantable medical devices including such devices as pacemakers and artificial hearts.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/resonant-inductive-coupling] While the early systems used a resonant receiver coil, later systems implemented resonant transmitter coils as well.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/resonant-inductive-coupling] These medical devices are designed for high efficiency using low power electronics while efficiently accommodating some misalignment and dynamic twisting of the coils.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/resonant-inductive-coupling] The separation between the coils in implantable applications is commonly less than 20 cm.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/resonant-inductive-coupling] Today resonant inductive energy transfer is regularly used for providing electric power in many commercially available medical implantable devices.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/resonant-inductive-coupling] Wireless electric energy transfer for experimentally powering electric automobiles and buses is a higher power application (>10 kW) of resonant inductive energy transfer.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/resonant-inductive-coupling] High power levels are required for rapid recharging and high energy transfer efficiency is required both for operational economy and to avoid negative environmental impact of the system.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/resonant-inductive-coupling] An experimental electrified roadway test track built circa 1990 achieved just above 60% energy efficiency while recharging the battery of a prototype bus at a specially equipped bus stop.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/resonant-inductive-coupling] The bus could be outfitted with a retractable receiving coil for greater coil clearance when moving.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/resonant-inductive-coupling] The gap between the transmit and receive coils was designed to be less than 10 cm when powered.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/resonant-inductive-coupling] In addition to buses the use of wireless transfer has been investigated for recharging electric automobiles in parking spots and garages as well.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/resonant-inductive-coupling] Some of these wireless resonant inductive devices operate at low milliwatt power levels and are battery powered.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/resonant-inductive-coupling] Others operate at higher kilowatt power levels.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/resonant-inductive-coupling] Current implantable medical and road electrification device designs achieve more than 75% transfer efficiency at an operating distance between the transmit and receive coils of less than 10 cm.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/resonant-inductive-coupling] In 1993, Professor John Boys and Professor Grant Covic, of the University of Auckland in New Zealand, developed systems to transfer large amounts of energy across small air gaps.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/resonant-inductive-coupling] It was putting into practical use as the moving crane and the AGV non-contact power supply in Japan.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/resonant-inductive-coupling] In 1998, RFID tags were patented that were powered in this way.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/resonant-inductive-coupling] In November 2006, Marin Soljačić and other researchers at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology applied this near field behavior to wireless power transmission, based on strongly-coupled resonators.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/resonant-inductive-coupling] In a theoretical analysis, they demonstrate that, by designing electromagnetic resonators that suffer minimal loss due to radiation and absorption and have a near field with mid-range extent (namely a few times the resonator size), mid-range efficient wireless energy-transfer is possible.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/resonant-inductive-coupling] The reason is that, if two such resonant circuits tuned to the same frequency are within a fraction of a wavelength, their near fields (consisting of 'evanescent waves') couple by means of evanescent wave coupling.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/resonant-inductive-coupling] Oscillating waves develop between the inductors, which can allow the energy to transfer from one object to the other within times much shorter than all loss times, which were designed to be long, and thus with the maximum possible energy-transfer efficiency.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/resonant-inductive-coupling] Since the resonant wavelength is much larger than the resonators, the field can circumvent extraneous objects in the vicinity and thus this mid-range energy-transfer scheme does not require line-of-sight.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/resonant-inductive-coupling] By utilizing in particular the magnetic field to achieve the coupling, this method can be safe, since magnetic fields interact weakly with living organisms.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/resonant-inductive-coupling] Apple Inc. applied for a patent on the technology in 2010, after WiPower did so in 2008.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/resonant-inductive-coupling] In the past, the power source used on the JR Tokai SCMaglev car was generating with a gas turbine generator.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/resonant-inductive-coupling] In 2011, they succeeded in powering while driving (CWD:charge while driving) across a large gap by the JR Tokai proprietary 9.8 kHz phase synchronization technology developed based on technology similar to AGV's wireless power scheme.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/resonant-inductive-coupling] And the Japanese Ministry of Land, Infrastructure and Transportation evaluated the technology as all the problems for practical use were cleared.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/resonant-inductive-coupling] Construction of SCMaglev begin and commercial use will start in 2027.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/resonant-inductive-coupling] Non-resonant coupled inductors, such as typical transformers, work on the principle of a primary coil generating a magnetic field and a secondary coil subtending as much as possible of that field so that the power passing through the secondary is as close as possible to that of the primary.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/resonant-inductive-coupling] This requirement that the field be covered by the secondary results in very short range and usually requires a magnetic core.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/resonant-inductive-coupling] Over greater distances the non-resonant induction method is highly inefficient and wastes the vast majority of the energy in resistive losses of the primary coil.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/resonant-inductive-coupling] Using resonance can help improve efficiency dramatically.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/resonant-inductive-coupling] If resonant coupling is used, the secondary coil is capacitive loaded so as to form a tuned LC circuit.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/resonant-inductive-coupling] If the primary coil is driven at the secondary side resonant frequency, it turns out that significant power may be transmitted between the coils over a range of a few times the coil diameters at reasonable efficiency.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/resonant-inductive-coupling] Compared to the costs associated with batteries, particularly non-rechargeable batteries, the costs of the batteries are hundreds of times higher.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/resonant-inductive-coupling] In situations where a source of power is available nearby, it can be a cheaper solution.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/resonant-inductive-coupling] In addition, whereas batteries need periodic maintenance and replacement, resonant energy transfer can be used instead.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/resonant-inductive-coupling] Batteries additionally generate pollution during their construction and their disposal which is largely avoided.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/resonant-inductive-coupling] Unlike mains-wired equipment, no direct electrical connection is needed and hence equipment can be sealed to minimize the possibility of electric shock.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/resonant-inductive-coupling] Because the coupling is achieved using predominantly magnetic fields; the technology may be relatively safe.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/resonant-inductive-coupling] Safety standards and guidelines do exist in most countries for electromagnetic field exposures (e.g.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/resonant-inductive-coupling] Whether the system can meet the guidelines or the less stringent legal requirements depends on the delivered power and range from the transmitter.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/resonant-inductive-coupling] Deployed systems already generate magnetic fields, for example induction cookers in the tens of kHz where high fields are permitted, and contactless smart card readers, where higher frequency is possible as the required energies are lower.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/resonant-inductive-coupling] A study for the Swedish military found that 85 kHz systems for dynamic wireless power transfer for vehicles can cause electromagnetic interference at a radius of up to 300 kilometers.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/resonant-inductive-coupling] This process occurs in a resonant transformer, an electrical component which transformer consists of high Q coil wound on the same core with a capacitor connected across a coil to make a coupled LC circuit.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/resonant-inductive-coupling] The most basic resonant inductive coupling consists of one drive coil on the primary side and one resonance circuit on the secondary side.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/resonant-inductive-coupling] In this case, when the resonant state on the secondary side is observed from the primary side, two resonances as a pair are observed.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/resonant-inductive-coupling] One of them is called the antiresonant frequency (parallel resonant frequency 1), and the other is called the resonant frequency (serial resonant frequency 1').
[src:wireless-power-transfer/resonant-inductive-coupling] The short-circuit inductance and resonant capacitor of the secondary coil are combined into a resonant circuit.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/resonant-inductive-coupling] When the primary coil is driven with a resonant frequency (serial resonant frequency) of the secondary side, the phases of the magnetic fields of the primary coil and the secondary coil are synchronized.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/resonant-inductive-coupling] As a result, the maximum voltage is generated on the secondary coil due to the increase of the mutual flux, and the copper loss of the primary coil is reduced, the heat generation is reduced, and the efficiency is relatively improved.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/resonant-inductive-coupling] The resonant inductive coupling is the near field wireless transmission of electrical energy between magnetically coupled coils, which is part of a resonant circuit tuned to resonate at the same frequency as the driving frequency.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/resonant-inductive-coupling] In the transformer, only part of the flux generated by current through the primary coil is coupled to the secondary coil and vice versa.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/resonant-inductive-coupling] The part that couples is called *mutual flux* and the part that does not couple is called *leakage flux*.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/resonant-inductive-coupling] When the system is not in the resonance state, this leads to the open-circuit voltage appearing at the secondary being less than predicted by the turns ratio of the coils.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/resonant-inductive-coupling] The degree of coupling is captured by a parameter called *coupling coefficient*.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/resonant-inductive-coupling] The coupling coefficient, k, is defined as the ratio of transformer open-circuit voltage ratio to the ratio that would be obtained if all the flux coupled from one coil to the other.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/resonant-inductive-coupling] However, if it is not open circuit, the flux ratio will change.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/resonant-inductive-coupling] Each coil inductance can be notionally divided into two parts in the proportions *k*:(1−*k*).
[src:wireless-power-transfer/resonant-inductive-coupling] These are respectively an inductance producing the mutual flux and an inductance producing the leakage flux.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/resonant-inductive-coupling] Coupling coefficient is a function of the geometry of the system.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/resonant-inductive-coupling] It is fixed by the positional relationship between the two coils.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/resonant-inductive-coupling] The coupling coefficient does not change between when the system is in the resonance state and when it is not in the resonance state, or even if the system is in resonance state and a secondary voltage larger than the turns ratio is generated.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/resonant-inductive-coupling] However, in the resonance case, the flux ratio changes and the mutual flux increases.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/resonant-inductive-coupling] Resonant systems are said to be tightly coupled, loosely coupled, critically coupled or overcoupled.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/resonant-inductive-coupling] Tight coupling is when the coupling coefficient is around 1 as with conventional iron-core transformers.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/resonant-inductive-coupling] Overcoupling is when the secondary coil is so close and the formation of mutual flux is hindered by the effect of antiresonance, and critical coupling is when the transfer in the passband is optimal.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/resonant-inductive-coupling] Loose coupling is when the coils are distant from each other, so that most of the flux misses the secondary.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/resonant-inductive-coupling] In Tesla coils around 0.2 is used, and at greater distances, for example for inductive wireless power transmission, it may be lower than 0.01.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/resonant-inductive-coupling] Generally the voltage gain of non resonantly coupled coils is directly proportional to the square root of the ratio of secondary and primary inductances.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/resonant-inductive-coupling] However, if in the state of resonant coupling, higher voltage is generated.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/resonant-inductive-coupling] The short-circuit inductance Lsc2 on the secondary side can be obtained by the following formula.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/resonant-inductive-coupling] The short-circuit inductance Lsc2 and the resonance capacitor Cr on the secondary side resonate.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/resonant-inductive-coupling] The resonance frequency ω2 is as follows.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/resonant-inductive-coupling] Assuming that the load resistance is Rl, the Q value of the secondary resonance circuit is as follows.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/resonant-inductive-coupling] The voltage generated in the resonance capacitor Cr at the peak of the resonance frequency is proportional to the Q value.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/resonant-inductive-coupling] In the case of the Type P-P, Q1 does not contribute to the voltage gain.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/resonant-inductive-coupling] The WiTricity type magnetic resonance is characterized in that the resonant coils on the primary side and the resonant coils on the secondary side are paired.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/resonant-inductive-coupling] The primary resonant coil increases the primary driving coil current and increases the generated magnetic flux around the primary resonator.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/resonant-inductive-coupling] This is equivalent to driving the primary coil at high voltage.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/resonant-inductive-coupling] In the case of the type on the left figure, the general principle is that if a given oscillating amount of energy (for example a pulse or a series of pulses) is placed into a primary coil which is capacitively loaded, the coil will 'ring', and form an oscillating magnetic field.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/resonant-inductive-coupling] Resonant transfer works by making a coil *ring* with an oscillating current.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/resonant-inductive-coupling] This generates an oscillating magnetic field.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/resonant-inductive-coupling] Because the coil is highly resonant, any energy placed in the coil dies away relatively slowly over very many cycles; but if a second coil is brought near it, the coil can pick up most of the energy before it is lost, even if it is some distance away.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/resonant-inductive-coupling] The fields used are predominantly non-radiative, near fields (sometimes called evanescent waves), as all hardware is kept well within the 1/4 wavelength distance they radiate little energy from the transmitter to infinity.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/resonant-inductive-coupling] The energy will transfer back and forth between the magnetic field in the inductor and the electric field across the capacitor at the resonant frequency.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/resonant-inductive-coupling] This oscillation will die away at a rate determined by the gain-bandwidth (*Q* factor), mainly due to resistive and radiative losses.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/resonant-inductive-coupling] However, provided the secondary coil cuts enough of the field that it absorbs more energy than is lost in each cycle of the primary, then most of the energy can still be transferred.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/resonant-inductive-coupling] Where *Q1* and *Q2* are the Q factors of the source and receiver coils respectively, and *k* is the coupling coefficient described above.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/resonant-inductive-coupling] Unlike the multiple-layer secondary of a non-resonant transformer, coils for this purpose are often single layer solenoids (to minimise skin effect and give improved *Q*) in parallel with a suitable capacitor.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/resonant-inductive-coupling] Alternative resonator geometries include wave-wound Litz wire and loop-gap resonators (LGRs).
[src:wireless-power-transfer/resonant-inductive-coupling] In the Litz wire-based resonators, insulation is either absent or low permittivity and low-loss materials such as silk are used to minimise dielectric losses.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/resonant-inductive-coupling] The LGR geometries have the advantage that electric fields outside the resonator structure are very weak which minimizes human exposure to electric fields and makes the power transfer efficiency insensitive to nearby dielectrics.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/resonant-inductive-coupling] To progressively feed energy into the primary coil with each cycle, different circuits can be used.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/resonant-inductive-coupling] One circuit employs a Colpitts oscillator.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/resonant-inductive-coupling] In Tesla coils an intermittent switching system, a "circuit controller" or "break," is used to inject an impulsive signal into the primary coil; the secondary coil then rings and decays.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/resonant-inductive-coupling] The secondary receiver coils are similar designs to the primary sending coils.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/resonant-inductive-coupling] Running the secondary at the same resonant frequency as the primary ensures that the secondary has a low impedance at the transmitter's frequency and that the energy is optimally absorbed.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/resonant-inductive-coupling] To remove energy from the secondary coil, different methods can be used, the AC can be used directly or rectified and a regulator circuit can be used to generate DC voltage.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] Wireless power techniques mainly fall into two categories: Near and far field.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] In *near field* or *non-radiative* techniques, power is transferred over short distances by magnetic fields using inductive coupling between coils of wire, or by electric fields using capacitive coupling between metal electrodes.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] In *far-field* or *radiative* techniques, also called *power beaming*, power is transferred by beams of electromagnetic radiation, like microwaves or laser beams.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] These techniques can transport energy longer distances but must be aimed at the receiver.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] Proposed applications for this type include solar power satellites and wireless powered drone aircraft.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] An important issue associated with all wireless power systems is limiting the exposure of people and other living beings to potentially injurious electromagnetic fields.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] Wireless power transfer is a generic term for technologies for transmitting energy by means of electromagnetic fields.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] At the transmitter the input power is converted to an oscillating electromagnetic field by some type of "antenna" device.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] The word "antenna" is used loosely here; it may be a coil of wire which generates a magnetic field, a metal plate which generates an electric field, an antenna which radiates radio waves, or a laser which generates light.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] A similar antenna or coupling device at the receiver converts the oscillating fields to an electric current.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] An important parameter that determines the type of waves is the frequency, which determines the wavelength.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] Wireless power uses the same fields and waves as wireless communication devices like radio, another familiar technology that involves electrical energy transmitted without wires by electromagnetic fields, used in cellphones, radio and television broadcasting, and WiFi.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] In radio communication the goal is the transmission of information, so the amount of power reaching the receiver is not so important, as long as it is sufficient that the information can be received intelligibly.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] In wireless communication technologies only tiny amounts of power reach the receiver.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] In contrast, with wireless power transfer the amount of energy received is the important thing, so the efficiency (fraction of transmitted energy that is received) is the more significant parameter.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] For this reason, wireless power technologies are likely to be more limited by distance than wireless communication technologies.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] Wireless power transfer may be used to power up wireless information transmitters or receivers.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] This type of communication is known as wireless powered communication (WPC).
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] The 19th century saw many developments of theories, and counter-theories on how electrical energy might be transmitted.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] In 1826, André-Marie Ampère discovered a connection between current and magnets.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] Michael Faraday described in 1831 with his law of induction the electromotive force was driving a current in a conductor loop by a time-varying magnetic flux.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] Transmission of electrical energy without wires was observed by many inventors and experimenters, but lack of a coherent theory attributed these phenomena vaguely to electromagnetic induction.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] A concise explanation of these phenomena would come from the 1860s Maxwell's equations by James Clerk Maxwell, establishing a theory that unified electricity and magnetism to electromagnetism, predicting the existence of electromagnetic waves as the "wireless" carrier of electromagnetic energy.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] Around 1884 John Henry Poynting defined the Poynting vector and gave Poynting's theorem, which describe the flow of power across an area within electromagnetic radiation and allow for a correct analysis of wireless power transfer systems.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] This was followed on by Heinrich Rudolf Hertz' 1888 validation of the theory, which included the evidence for radio waves.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] During the same period two schemes of wireless signaling were put forward by William Henry Ward (1871) and Mahlon Loomis (1872) that were based on the erroneous belief that there was an electrified atmospheric stratum accessible at low altitude.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] Both inventors' patents noted this layer connected with a return path using "Earth currents"' would allow for wireless telegraphy as well as supply power for the telegraph, doing away with artificial batteries, and could also be used for lighting, heat, and motive power.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] A more practical demonstration of wireless transmission via conduction came in Amos Dolbear's 1879 magneto electric telephone that used ground conduction to transmit over a distance of a quarter of a mile.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] After 1890, inventor Nikola Tesla experimented with transmitting power by inductive and capacitive coupling using spark-excited radio frequency resonant transformers, now called Tesla coils, which generated high AC voltages.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] Early on he attempted to develop a wireless lighting system based on near-field inductive and capacitive coupling and conducted a series of public demonstrations where he lit Geissler tubes and even incandescent light bulbs from across a stage.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] He found he could increase the distance at which he could light a lamp by using a receiving LC circuit tuned to resonance with the transmitter's LC circuit. using resonant inductive coupling.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] Tesla failed to make a commercial product out of his findings but his resonant inductive coupling method is now widely used in electronics and is currently being applied to short-range wireless power systems.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] Experiment in resonant inductive transfer by Tesla at Colorado Springs 1899.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] The coil is in resonance with Tesla's magnifying transmitter nearby, powering the light bulb at bottom.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] Tesla's unsuccessful Wardenclyffe power station.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] Tesla went on to develop a wireless power distribution system that he hoped would be capable of transmitting power long distance directly into homes and factories.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] To further study the conductive nature of low pressure air he set up a test facility at high altitude in Colorado Springs during 1899.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] Experiments he conducted there with a large coil operating in the megavolts range, as well as observations he made of the electronic noise of lightning strikes, led him to conclude incorrectly that he could use the entire globe of the Earth to conduct electrical energy.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] The theory included driving alternating current pulses into the Earth at its resonant frequency from a grounded Tesla coil working against an elevated capacitance to make the potential of the Earth oscillate.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] Tesla thought this would allow alternating current to be received with a similar capacitive antenna tuned to resonance with it at any point on Earth with very little power loss.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] His observations also led him to believe a high voltage used in a coil at an elevation of a few hundred feet would "break the air stratum down", eliminating the need for miles of cable hanging on balloons to create his atmospheric return circuit.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] Tesla would go on the next year to propose a "World Wireless System" that was to broadcast both information and power worldwide.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] In 1901, at Shoreham, New York he attempted to construct a large high-voltage wireless power station, now called Wardenclyffe Tower, but by 1904 investment dried up and the facility was never completed.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] Before World War II, little progress was made in wireless power transmission.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] Radio was developed for communication uses, but could not be used for power transmission since the relatively low-frequency radio waves spread out in all directions and little energy reached the receiver.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] In radio communication, at the receiver, an amplifier intensifies a weak signal using energy from another source.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] For power transmission, efficient transmission required transmitters that could generate higher-frequency microwaves, which can be focused in narrow beams towards a receiver.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] The development of microwave technology during World War II, such as the klystron and magnetron tubes and parabolic antennas, made some radiative (far-field) methods practical for the first time, and the first long-distance wireless power transmission was achieved in the 1960s by William C.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] In 1964, Brown invented the rectenna which could efficiently convert microwaves to DC power, and in 1964 demonstrated it with the first wireless-powered aircraft, a model helicopter powered by microwaves beamed from the ground.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] Electric and magnetic fields are created by charged particles in matter such as electrons.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] A stationary charge creates an electrostatic field in the space around it.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] A steady current of charges (direct current, DC) creates a static magnetic field around it.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] These fields contain energy, but cannot carry power because they are static.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] However time-varying fields can carry power.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] Accelerating electric charges, such as are found in an alternating current (AC) of electrons in a wire, create time-varying electric and magnetic fields in the space around them.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] These fields can exert oscillating forces on the electrons in a receiving "antenna", causing them to move back and forth.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] These represent alternating current which can be used to power a load.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] The oscillating electric and magnetic fields surrounding moving electric charges in an antenna device can be divided into two regions, depending on distance *D*range from the antenna.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] The boundary between the regions is somewhat vaguely defined.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] At large relative distance, the near-field components of electric and magnetic fields are approximately quasi-static oscillating dipole fields.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] These fields decrease with the cube of distance: (*D*range / *D*ant)−3 Since power is proportional to the square of the field strength, the power transferred decreases as (*D*range / *D*ant)−6. or 60 dB per decade.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] In other words, if far apart, increasing the distance between the two antennas tenfold causes the power received to decrease by a factor of 106 = 1000000.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] As a result, inductive and capacitive coupling can be used only for short-range power transfer, within a few times the diameter of the antenna device *D*ant.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] Unlike in a radiative system where the maximum radiation occurs when the dipole antennas are oriented transverse to the direction of propagation, with dipole fields the maximum coupling occurs when the dipoles are oriented longitudinally.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] inductive charging spots in a coffee shop.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] Customers can set their phones and computers on them to recharge.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] Left: modern inductive power transfer, an electric toothbrush charger.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] A coil in the stand produces a magnetic field, inducing an alternating current in a coil in the toothbrush, which is rectified to charge the batteries.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] In inductive coupling (*electromagnetic induction* or *inductive power transfer*, IPT), power is transferred between coils of wire by a magnetic field.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] The transmitter and receiver coils together form a transformer.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] An alternating current (AC) through the transmitter coil *(L1)* creates an oscillating magnetic field *(B)* by Ampere's law.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] The magnetic field passes through the receiving coil *(L2)*, where it induces an alternating EMF (voltage) by Faraday's law of induction, which creates an alternating current in the receiver.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] The induced alternating current may either drive the load directly, or be rectified to direct current (DC) by a rectifier in the receiver, which drives the load.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] Inductive coupling is the oldest and most widely used wireless power technology, and virtually the only one so far which is used in commercial products.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] It is used in inductive charging stands for cordless appliances used in wet environments such as electric toothbrushes and shavers, to reduce the risk of electric shock.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] Another application area is "transcutaneous" recharging of biomedical prosthetic devices implanted in the human body, such as cardiac pacemakers, to avoid having wires passing through the skin.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] It is also used to charge electric vehicles such as cars and to either charge or power transit vehicles like buses and trains.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] However the fastest growing use is wireless charging pads to recharge mobile and handheld wireless devices such as laptop and tablet computers, computer mouse, cellphones, digital media players, and video game controllers.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] In the United States, the Federal Communications Commission (FCC) provided its first certification for a wireless transmission charging system in December 2017.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] The power transferred increases with frequency and the mutual inductance M between the coils, which depends on their geometry and the distance $D_{\text{range}}$ between them.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] A widely used figure of merit is the coupling coefficient $k\;=\;M/{\sqrt {L_{1}L_{2}}}$ .
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] This dimensionless parameter is equal to the fraction of magnetic flux through the transmitter coil $L1$ that passes through the receiver coil $L2$ when L2 is open circuited.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] If the two coils are on the same axis and close together so all the magnetic flux from $L1$ passes through $L2$ , $k=1$ and the link efficiency approaches 100%.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] The greater the separation between the coils, the more of the magnetic field from the first coil misses the second, and the lower k and the link efficiency are, approaching zero at large separations.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] The link efficiency and power transferred is roughly proportional to $k^{2}$ .
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] In order to achieve high efficiency, the coils must be very close together, a fraction of the coil diameter $D_{\text{ant}}$ , usually within centimeters, with the coils' axes aligned.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] Wide, flat coil shapes are usually used, to increase coupling.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] Ferrite "flux confinement" cores can confine the magnetic fields, improving coupling and reducing interference to nearby electronics, but they are heavy and bulky so small wireless devices often use air-core coils.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] Ordinary inductive coupling can achieve high efficiency only when the coils are very close together, usually adjacent.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] In most modern inductive systems resonant inductive coupling is used, in which the efficiency is increased by using resonant circuits.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] This can achieve high efficiencies at greater distances than nonresonant inductive coupling.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] Resonant inductive coupling (*electrodynamic coupling*, *strongly coupled magnetic resonance*) is a form of inductive coupling in which power is transferred by magnetic fields *(B, green)* between two resonant circuits (tuned circuits), one in the transmitter and one in the receiver.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] Each resonant circuit consists of a coil of wire connected to a capacitor, or a self-resonant coil or other resonator with internal capacitance.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] The two are tuned to resonate at the same resonant frequency.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] The resonance between the coils can greatly increase coupling and power transfer, analogously to the way a vibrating tuning fork can induce sympathetic vibration in a distant fork tuned to the same pitch.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] Nikola Tesla first discovered resonant coupling during his pioneering experiments in wireless power transfer around the turn of the 20th century, but the possibilities of using resonant coupling to increase transmission range has only recently been explored.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] In 2007 a team led by Marin Soljačić at MIT used two coupled tuned circuits each made of a 25 cm self-resonant coil of wire at 10 MHz to achieve the transmission of 60 W of power over a distance of 2 meters (6.6 ft) (8 times the coil diameter) at around 40% efficiency.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] The concept behind resonant inductive coupling systems is that high Q factor resonators exchange energy at a much higher rate than they lose energy due to internal damping.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] Therefore, by using resonance, the same amount of power can be transferred at greater distances, using the much weaker magnetic fields out in the peripheral regions ("tails") of the near fields.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] Resonant inductive coupling can achieve high efficiency at ranges of 4 to 10 times the coil diameter (*D*ant).
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] This is called "mid-range" transfer, in contrast to the "short range" of nonresonant inductive transfer, which can achieve similar efficiencies only when the coils are adjacent.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] Another advantage is that resonant circuits interact with each other so much more strongly than they do with nonresonant objects that power losses due to absorption in stray nearby objects are negligible.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] Resonant technology is currently being widely incorporated in modern inductive wireless power systems.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] One of the possibilities envisioned for this technology is area wireless power coverage.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] A coil in the wall or ceiling of a room might be able to wirelessly power lights and mobile devices anywhere in the room, with reasonable efficiency.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] An environmental and economic benefit of wirelessly powering small devices such as clocks, radios, music players and remote controls is that it could drastically reduce the 6 billion batteries disposed of each year, a large source of toxic waste and groundwater contamination.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] Capacitive coupling also referred to as electric coupling, makes use of electric fields for the transmission of power between two electrodes (an anode and cathode) forming a capacitance for the transfer of power.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] In capacitive coupling (electrostatic induction), the conjugate of inductive coupling, energy is transmitted by electric fields between electrodes such as metal plates.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] The transmitter and receiver electrodes form a capacitor, with the intervening space as the dielectric.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] An alternating voltage generated by the transmitter is applied to the transmitting plate, and the oscillating electric field induces an alternating potential on the receiver plate by electrostatic induction, which causes an alternating current to flow in the load circuit.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] The amount of power transferred increases with the frequency the square of the voltage, and the capacitance between the plates, which is proportional to the area of the smaller plate and (for short distances) inversely proportional to the separation.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] Capacitive coupling has only been used practically in a few low power applications, because the very high voltages on the electrodes required to transmit significant power can be hazardous, and can cause unpleasant side effects such as noxious ozone production.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] In addition, in contrast to magnetic fields, electric fields interact strongly with most materials, including the human body, due to dielectric polarization.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] Intervening materials between or near the electrodes can absorb the energy, in the case of humans possibly causing excessive electromagnetic field exposure.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] However capacitive coupling has a few advantages over inductive coupling.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] The field is largely confined between the capacitor plates, reducing interference, which in inductive coupling requires heavy ferrite "flux confinement" cores.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] Also, alignment requirements between the transmitter and receiver are less critical.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] Capacitive coupling has recently been applied to charging battery powered portable devices as well as charging or continuous wireless power transfer in biomedical implants, and is being considered as a means of transferring power between substrate layers in integrated circuits.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] Resonance can also be used with capacitive coupling to extend the range.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] At the turn of the 20th century, Nikola Tesla did the first experiments with both resonant inductive and capacitive coupling.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] An electrodynamic wireless power transfer (EWPT) system utilizes a receiver with a mechanically resonating or rotating permanent magnet.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] When subjected to a time-varying magnetic field, the mechanical motion of the resonating magnet is converted into electricity by one or more electromechanical transduction schemes (e.g. electromagnetic/induction, piezoelectric, or capacitive).
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] For EWPT devices having identical resonant frequencies, the magnitude of power transfer is entirely dependent on critical coupling coefficient, denoted by k , between the transmitter and receiver devices.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] For coupled resonators with same resonant frequencies, wireless power transfer between the transmitter and the receiver is spread over three regimes – under-coupled, critically coupled and over-coupled.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] This critical coupling coefficient is demonstrated to be a function of distance between the source and the receiver devices.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] In this method, power is transmitted between two rotating armatures, one in the transmitter and one in the receiver, which rotate synchronously, coupled together by a magnetic field generated by permanent magnets on the armatures.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] The transmitter armature is turned either by or as the rotor of an electric motor, and its magnetic field exerts torque on the receiver armature, turning it.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] The magnetic field acts like a mechanical coupling between the armatures.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] The receiver armature produces power to drive the load, either by turning a separate electric generator or by using the receiver armature itself as the rotor in a generator.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] This device has been proposed as an alternative to inductive power transfer for noncontact charging of electric vehicles.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] A rotating armature embedded in a garage floor or curb would turn a receiver armature in the underside of the vehicle to charge its batteries.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] It is claimed that this technique can transfer power over distances of 10 to 15 cm (4 to 6 inches) with high efficiency, over 90%.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] Also, the low frequency stray magnetic fields produced by the rotating magnets produce less electromagnetic interference to nearby electronic devices than the high frequency magnetic fields produced by inductive coupling systems.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] A prototype system charging electric vehicles has been in operation at University of British Columbia since 2012.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] Other researchers, however, claim that the two energy conversions (electrical to mechanical to electrical again) make the system less efficient than electrical systems like inductive coupling.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] A new kind of system using the Zenneck type waves was shown by Oruganti et al., where they demonstrated that it was possible to excite Zenneck wave type waves on flat metal-air interfaces and transmit power across metal obstacles.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] Here the idea is to excite a localized charge oscillation at the metal-air interface, the resulting modes propagate along the metal-air interface.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] Far field methods achieve longer ranges, often multiple kilometer ranges, where the distance is much greater than the diameter of the device(s).
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] High-directivity antennas or well-collimated laser light produce a beam of energy that can be made to match the shape of the receiving area.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] The maximum directivity for antennas is physically limited by diffraction.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] In general, visible light (from lasers) and microwaves (from purpose-designed antennas) are the forms of electromagnetic radiation best suited to energy transfer.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] The dimensions of the components may be dictated by the distance from transmitter to receiver, the wavelength and the Rayleigh criterion or diffraction limit, used in standard radio frequency antenna design, which also applies to lasers.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] Airy's diffraction limit is also frequently used to determine an approximate spot size at an arbitrary distance from the aperture.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] Electromagnetic radiation experiences less diffraction at shorter wavelengths (higher frequencies); so, for example, a blue laser is diffracted less than a red one.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] The larger the ratio of a transmitting antenna's aperture or laser's exit aperture to the wavelength of radiation, the more the radiation can be concentrated in a compact beam.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] Microwave power beaming can be more efficient than lasers, and is less prone to atmospheric attenuation caused by dust or aerosols such as fog.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] Here, the power levels are calculated by combining the parameters together, and adding in the gains and losses due to the antenna characteristics and the transparency and dispersion of the medium through which the radiation passes.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] That process is known as calculating a link budget.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] Power transmission via radio waves can be made more directional, allowing longer-distance power beaming, with shorter wavelengths of electromagnetic radiation, typically in the microwave range.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] A rectenna may be used to convert the microwave energy back into electricity.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] Rectenna conversion efficiencies exceeding 95% have been realized.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] Power beaming using microwaves has been proposed for the transmission of energy from orbiting solar power satellites to Earth and the beaming of power to spacecraft leaving orbit has been considered.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] Power beaming by microwaves has the difficulty that, for most space applications, the required aperture sizes are very large due to diffraction limiting antenna directionality.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] For example, the 1978 NASA study of solar power satellites required a 1-kilometre-diameter (0.62 mi) transmitting antenna and a 10-kilometre-diameter (6.2 mi) receiving rectenna for a microwave beam at 2.45 GHz.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] These sizes can be somewhat decreased by using shorter wavelengths, although short wavelengths may have difficulties with atmospheric absorption and beam blockage by rain or water droplets.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] Because of the "thinned-array curse", it is not possible to make a narrower beam by combining the beams of several smaller satellites.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] For earthbound applications, a large-area 10 km diameter receiving array allows large total power levels to be used while operating at the low power density suggested for human electromagnetic exposure safety.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] A human safe power density of 1 mW/cm2 distributed across a 10 km diameter area corresponds to 750 megawatts total power level.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] This is the power level found in many modern electric power plants.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] For comparison, a solar PV farm of similar size might easily exceed 10,000 megawatts at best conditions during daytime.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] Following World War II, which saw the development of high-power microwave emitters known as cavity magnetrons, the idea of using microwaves to transfer power was researched.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] By 1964, a miniature helicopter propelled by microwave power had been demonstrated.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] Japanese researcher Hidetsugu Yagi also investigated wireless energy transmission using a directional array antenna that he designed.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] In February 1926, Yagi and his colleague Shintaro Uda published their first paper on the tuned high-gain directional array now known as the Yagi antenna.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] While it did not prove to be particularly useful for power transmission, this beam antenna has been widely adopted throughout the broadcasting and wireless telecommunications industries due to its excellent performance characteristics.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] Wireless high power transmission using microwaves is well proven.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] Experiments in the tens of kilowatts have been performed at the Goldstone Deep Space Communications Complex in California in 1975 and more recently (1997) at Grand Bassin on Reunion Island.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] These methods achieve distances on the order of a kilometer.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] Under experimental conditions, microwave conversion efficiency was measured to be around 54% across one meter.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] A change to 24 GHz has been suggested as microwave emitters similar to LEDs have been made with very high quantum efficiencies using negative resistance, i.e., Gunn or IMPATT diodes, and this would be viable for short range links.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] In 2013, inventor Hatem Zeine demonstrated how wireless power transmission using phased array antennas can deliver electrical power up to 30 feet.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] It uses the same radio frequencies as WiFi.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] In 2015, researchers at the University of Washington introduced power over Wi-Fi, which trickle-charges batteries and powered battery-free cameras and temperature sensors using transmissions from Wi-Fi routers.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] Wi-Fi signals were shown to power battery-free temperature and camera sensors at ranges of up to 20 feet.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] It was also shown that Wi-Fi can be used to wirelessly trickle-charge nickel–metal hydride and lithium-ion coin-cell batteries at distances of up to 28 feet.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] In 2017, the Federal Communications Commission (FCC) certified the first mid-field radio frequency (RF) transmitter of wireless power.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] In 2021 the FCC granted a license to an over-the-air (OTA) wireless charging system that combines near-field and far-field methods by using a frequency of about 900 MHz.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] Due to the radiated power of about 1 W this system is intended for small IoT devices as various sensors, trackers, detectors and monitors.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] Power can be transmitted by converting electricity into a laser beam that is received and concentrated onto photovoltaic cells (solar cells).
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] It exploits electromagnetic radiation closer to the visible region (.2 to 2 micrometers).
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] This mechanism is generally known as 'power beaming' because the power is beamed at a receiver that can convert it to electrical energy.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] At the receiver, power converters optimized for monochromatic light conversion are applied.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] Power beaming technology was explored in military applications and aerospace applications.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] Also, it powers sensors in industrial environments and for commercial and consumer electronics.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] Wireless energy transfer systems using lasers for consumer space have to satisfy laser safety requirements standardized under IEC 60825.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] The first wireless power system using lasers for consumer applications was Wi-Charge, demonstrated in 2018, capable of delivering power to stationary and moving devices across a room.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] This wireless power system complied with safety regulations.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] It is approved by the US Food and Drug Administration (FDA).
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] Other issues include propagation, and the coherence and the range limitation problem.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] NASA's Dryden Flight Research Center demonstrated a unmanned model plane powered by a laser beam, demonstrating the feasibility of periodic laser recharging.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] Scientists from the Chinese Academy of Sciences developed a proof-of-concept of utilizing a dual-wavelength laser to wirelessly charge portable devices or UAVs.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] In 2025 DARPA announced transmission of 800 watts for 30 seconds at a distance of 5.3 miles (8.6 km) at 20% efficiency, exceeding prior results of beaming 230 watts across one mile (1.7 km) for 25 seconds using its Power Receiver Array Demo (PRAD).
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] In atmospheric plasma channel coupling, energy is transferred between two electrodes by electrical conduction through ionized air.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] When an electric field gradient exists between the two electrodes, exceeding 34 kilovolts per centimeter at sea level atmospheric pressure, an electric arc occurs.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] This atmospheric dielectric breakdown results in the flow of electric current along a random trajectory through an ionized plasma channel between the two electrodes.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] An example of this is natural lightning, where one electrode is a virtual point in a cloud and the other is a point on Earth.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] Laser Induced Plasma Channel (LIPC) research is presently underway using ultrafast lasers to artificially promote development of the plasma channel through the air, directing the electric arc, and guiding the current across a specific path in a controllable manner.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] The laser energy reduces the atmospheric dielectric breakdown voltage and the air is made less insulating by superheating, which lowers the density ( p ) of the filament of air.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] In the context of wireless power, *energy harvesting*, also called *power harvesting* or *energy scavenging*, is the conversion of ambient energy from the environment to electric power, mainly to power small autonomous wireless electronic devices.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] The ambient energy may come from stray electric or magnetic fields or radio waves from nearby electrical equipment, light, thermal energy (heat), or kinetic energy such as vibration or motion of the device.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] Although the efficiency of conversion is usually low and the power gathered often minuscule (milliwatts or microwatts), it can be adequate to run or recharge small micropower wireless devices such as remote sensors, which are proliferating in many fields.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p01] This new technology is being developed to eliminate the need for battery replacement or charging of such wireless devices, allowing them to operate completely autonomously.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p02] Inductive power transfer between nearby wire coils was the earliest wireless power technology to be developed, existing since the transformer was developed in the 1800s.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p02] Induction heating has been used since the early 1900s and is used for induction cooking.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p02] With the advent of cordless devices, induction charging stands have been developed for appliances used in wet environments, like electric toothbrushes and electric razors, to eliminate the hazard of electric shock.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p02] One of the earliest proposed applications of inductive transfer was to power electric locomotives.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p02] In 1892 Maurice Hutin and Maurice Leblanc patented a wireless method of powering railroad trains using resonant coils inductively coupled to a track wire at 3 kHz.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p02] The first passive RFID (Radio Frequency Identification) technologies were invented by Mario Cardullo (1973) and Koelle et al.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p02] (1975) and by the 1990s were being used in proximity cards and contactless smartcards.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p02] The Wireless Power Consortium was established in 2008 to develop interoperable standards across manufacturers.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p02] Its Qi inductive power standard published in August 2009 enables high efficiency charging and powering of portable devices of up to 5 watts over distances of 4 cm (1.6 inches).
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p02] The wireless device is placed on a flat charger plate (which can be embedded in table tops at cafes, for example) and power is transferred from a flat coil in the charger to a similar one in the device.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p02] In 2007, a team led by Marin Soljačić at MIT used a dual resonance transmitter with a 25 cm diameter secondary tuned to 10 MHz to transfer 60 W of power to a similar dual resonance receiver over a distance of 2 meters (6.6 ft) (eight times the transmitter coil diameter) at around 40% efficiency.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p02] Tucker and Professor Kevin Warwick of the University of Reading, recreated Tesla's 1900 patent 0,645,576 in miniature and demonstrated power transmission over 4 meters (13 ft) with a coil diameter of 10 centimetres (3.9 in) at a resonant frequency of 27.50 MHz, with an effective efficiency of 60%.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p02] A major motivation for microwave research in the 1970s and 1980s was to develop a satellite for space-based solar power.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p02] Conceived in 1968 by Peter Glaser, this would harvest energy from sunlight using solar cells and beam it down to Earth as microwaves to huge rectennas, which would convert it to electrical energy on the electric power grid.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p02] In landmark 1975 experiments as technical director of a JPL/Raytheon program, Brown demonstrated long-range transmission by beaming 475 W of microwave power to a rectenna a mile away, with a microwave to DC conversion efficiency of 54%.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p02] At NASA's Jet Propulsion Laboratory, he and Robert Dickinson transmitted 30 kW DC output power across 1.5 km with 2.38 GHz microwaves from a 26 m dish to a 7.3 x 3.5 m rectenna array.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p02] The incident-RF to DC conversion efficiency of the rectenna was 80%.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p02] In 1983 Japan launched Microwave Ionosphere Nonlinear Interaction Experiment (MINIX), a rocket experiment to test transmission of high power microwaves through the ionosphere.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p02] In recent years a focus of research has been the development of wireless-powered drone aircraft, which began in 1959 with the Dept. of Defense's RAMP (Raytheon Airborne Microwave Platform) project which sponsored Brown's research.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p02] In 1987 Canada's Communications Research Center developed a small prototype airplane called Stationary High Altitude Relay Platform (SHARP) to relay telecommunication data between points on earth similar to a communications satellite.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p02] Powered by a rectenna, it could fly at 13 miles (21 km) altitude and stay aloft for months.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p02] In 1992 a team at Kyoto University built a more advanced craft called MILAX (MIcrowave Lifted Airplane eXperiment).
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p02] In 2003 NASA flew the first laser powered aircraft.
[src:wireless-power-transfer/wireless-power-transfer-p02] The small model plane's motor was powered by electricity generated by photocells from a beam of infrared light from a ground-based laser, while a control system kept the laser pointed at the plane.
